2. The pretreatment of my tree(s)

2.1. Tree file type transfer

my_tree <- read.tree("D:/9-毕业设计-venom evolution/3-phylogeneti_tree_resource/DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master/01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS/02-TREES/cnido_748_untrimmed_b.tre") # 使用绝对路径读取.tre文件
write.nexus(my_tree, file = "D:/9-毕业设计-venom evolution/3-phylogeneti_tree_resource/DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master/01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS/02-TREES/my_tree.nex") # 使用绝对路径,把之前的.tre文件写入.nex文件，完成格式转换

2.2. Make the tree ultrametric over and over again

ultratree <-chronopl(my_tree, 1, age.min = 1, age.max = NULL,
         node = "root", S = 1, tol = 1e-8,
         CV = FALSE, eval.max = 500, iter.max = 500) #可以用ape package的chronopl函数，ultrametric处理
write.tree(ultratree, file = "D:/9-毕业设计-venom evolution/3-phylogeneti_tree_resource/DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master/01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS/02-TREES/ultratree.tre") #把ultrametric处理了的tree，写成.tre文件保存
cnidophylo <- read.nexus("D:/9-毕业设计-venom evolution/3-phylogeneti_tree_resource/DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master/01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS/02-TREES/my_tree.nex")
ultracnidophylo <- chronopl(cnidophylo, 1, age.min = 1, age.max = NULL,
         node = "root", S = 1, tol = 1e-8,
         CV = FALSE, eval.max = 500, iter.max = 500)
write.nexus(ultracnidophylo, file = "D:/9-毕业设计-venom evolution/3-phylogeneti_tree_resource/DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master/01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS/02-TREES/ultracnidophylo.nex")

2.3. Check if the tree is ultrametric

is.ultrametric(ultracnidophylo)
## [1] TRUE

2.4. Rename the tips of phylogeny

changed_name_all_species <- read.tree("D:\\9-毕业设计-venom evolution\\3-phylogeneti_tree_resource\\DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master\\01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS\\02-TREES\\changed_name_all_species.tre")
tip_labels <- changed_name_all_species$tip.label
write.csv(tip_labels, file = "tip_labels.csv", row.names = FALSE)
tipnames <- read.csv("D:\\9-毕业设计-venom evolution\\3-phylogeneti_tree_resource\\DeBiasse_cnidophylogenomics-master\\01-PHYLOGENOMIC_ANALYSIS\\02-TREES\\Tipname.csv")$Tipname

pruned_tree <- read.tree("your_pruned_tree.tre")

3. Final tree visualization

p1 <-ggtree(
   pruned_tree,
   mapping = NULL,
  layout = "rectangular",
  mrsd = NULL,
  as.Date = FALSE,
  yscale = "none",
  yscale_mapping = NULL,
  ladderize = TRUE,
  right = FALSE,
  branch.length = "branch.length",
  root.position = 0,
  xlim = NULL,
  layout.params = list(),
  hang = 0.1)
 p2 <- p1 + geom_tiplab(size = 2) + theme(
  axis.text = element_text(family = "Arial", size = 3, color = "black")
)
p2

# ggsave("my_test_tree.pdf", dpi = 300, width = 16, height = 15, units = "in")
tip_names <- pruned_tree$tip.label
tip_names_df <- data.frame(Tipname = tip_names)
write.csv(tip_names_df, file = "pruned_tip_names.csv", row.names = FALSE)
pruned_tree <- read.tree("your_pruned_tree.tre")
ultra_pruned_tree <- chronopl(pruned_tree, 1, age.min = 1, age.max = NULL,
         node = "root", S = 1, tol = 1e-8,
         CV = FALSE, eval.max = 500, iter.max = 500)
is.ultrametric(ultra_pruned_tree)
## [1] TRUE

4. Phylogenetic covariance (PCOV) analysis

4.1. Imput files

first we input some necessary files - tree file (.nex)

write.nexus(ultra_pruned_tree, file = "ultra_pruned_tree.nex")
NEX_tree <- read.nexus("ultra_pruned_tree.nex") # input the tree file
NEX_tree <- ladderize(NEX_tree, right = FALSE) # Order tree to make it nicer when plotting
plotTree(NEX_tree)

is.ultrametric(NEX_tree)
## [1] TRUE
NEX_tree_VCV <- vcv(NEX_tree)
NEX_tree_cor <- cov2cor(NEX_tree_VCV)

接下来，我们计算系统发生树的相关性矩阵，来换一种方式可视化种间的亲缘关系

#读取矩阵文件
NEX_tree_df <- as.data.frame(NEX_tree_cor)


#转置成基因为列
NEX_tree_df_t <- t(NEX_tree_df)

#计算基因间的相关性
#计算相关性的方法有"pearson", "spearman", "kendall"
NEX_tree_df_t_cor <- cor(NEX_tree_df_t, method="pearson") 

#绘图
pdf("NEX_tree_heatmap.pdf")

p_for_NEX_tree <- corrplot(NEX_tree_df_t_cor, 
  method = "pie",   
  type = "upper",
  
  col = colorRampPalette(c('#025259', '#007172', '#f4e2de', '#f29325', '#d94f04'))(100),
  tl.cex=0.4,  #文本标签的字体大小
  tl.col ="black",  #文本标签的颜色设置
  tl.offset=0.5,  #文本标签横着方向上的偏移量
  tl.srt=90,  #文本标签的倾斜角度
  diag = T,
  mar = c(0,2,0,2))  #设置图的四周间距

print(p_for_NEX_tree)

4.2. Matrix inverse

We need to calculate the inverse matrix to get the identity matrix (I) so as to reduce computations

inv.phylo = inverseA(NEX_tree, nodes = "TIPS", scale =TRUE)

4.3. Apply Markov chain Monte Carlo (Bayesian) generalised linear mixed model(MCMCglmm)

Part 1. What is MCMCglmm

The goal of the MCMCglmm (R package) is to model the effect of phylogeny on the top 10 components of cnidaria venom cocktail. - GLMM is a statistical model used to describe data with (1) random effects and (2) fixed effects. The mathematical expression of GLMM model is: \[ y = X * β + Z * u + ε \], where, y is the response variable, X is the matrix for fixed effects, β is the vector of fixed effects, Z is the matrix for random effects (means phylogeny here), u is the vector of random effects (associated with the inverse relationship matrix), and ε is the error term. - MCMC, which is a technique for approximating complex distributions through random sampling, was used here for parameter estimation

Part 2. Model running and considerations

All of the top 10 cnidaria venom toxins were normalized and passed as multi-response vectors by forming a matrix using the cbind function. trait was used to fit different response values, allowing them to have different means. The random effects were added as us(traits):species which allows us to obtain covariance across trait that are influenced by the effect of species (phylogeny), accounting for the covariance between two response variables. In our case where we have used phylogeny as the random effect, the vectors of random effects are associated with the inverse relationship matrix that we obtain via the inv.phylo command. The MCMC was run for a total of 200,000 iterations by nitt, with burn-in = 100000, and thin values = 15.

Part 3. Covariance model summary

# read the model
cov_model.1<-readRDS("cov_model_OnSango_sprandom_Final.nosize.20mil.rds")
cov_model.1$DIC  #Calculate the DIC value of the model
## [1] -1457.255
mean(summary(cov_model.1)$Gcovariances[,4]) # calculate the mean value
## [1] 454.8627

A smaller DIC (Deviance Information Criterion) value indicates a better fitting performance of the model. DIC considers following 2 things: (1) The average deviation of the future data prediction distribution; (2) The average deviation of the current data fitting effect. Therefore, DIC value is a comprehensive evaluation of model complexity and fitting performance. As for mean A larger mean sample size indicates a better fitting performance of the model because it means that each parameter has enough data support.

4.4. Generate the PCOV matrix

# 读取数据集
data_for_PCOV <- read.csv("your_data.csv", header=F)
gene_expression <- data_for_PCOV[1:53, 1:10]
# 计算协方差矩阵
cov_matrix <- cov(gene_expression)
rownames(cov_matrix) <- colnames(cov_matrix) <- c("TFTx", "BPP", "CRISP", "CTL", "GF", "KSPI", "LAAO", "PLA2", "SVMP", "SVSP")
# 将协方差矩阵转换为长格式
cov_matrix_long <- melt(cov_matrix)

# 绘制热图
heatmap_plot <- ggplot(cov_matrix_long, aes(x = Var1, y = Var2, fill = value)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "#a64036", mid = "white", high = "#354e6b",
                       midpoint = 0, limits = c(min(cov_matrix_long$value), max(cov_matrix_long$value)),
                       guide = "colorbar")  +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90, hjust=1)) +
  ggtitle("Covariance Matrix Heatmap")+
  geom_text(aes(label = round(value, 0.5)))

heatmap_plot

cov_matrix_0_1 <-cov2cor(cov_matrix)

  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "#a64036", mid = "white", high = "#354e6b",
                       midpoint = 0, limits = c(min(cov_matrix_long_0_1$value), max(cov_matrix_long_0_1$value)),
                       guide = "colorbar")  +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90, hjust=1)) +
  ggtitle("Covariance Matrix Heatmap")+
  geom_text(aes(label = round(value, 0.5)))

5. Calculating phylogenetic signal (λ)

We will have a brief introduction to the basic information of phylogenetic signal: Lambda (λ) is a measure of dependency of trait evolution with phylogeny. A signiﬁcant presence of a phylogenetic signal indicates that closely related species are likely to evolve the same way. Lambda values, are estimated as toxin variance on the diagonal, divided by the sum of diagonal variance and residuals.

5.1. The phylogenetic signal (λ) of TFTx

cov_model.1 <- readRDS("cov_model_OnSango_sprandom_Final.nosize.20mil.rds")
lambda.TFTx = cov_model.1$VCV[,"traitTFTx:traitTFTx.species"]/(cov_model.1$VCV[,"traitTFTx:traitTFTx.species"]+cov_model.1$VCV[,"traitTFTx:traitTFTx.units"]) # 从cov_model.1中，用VCV提取TFTx responsible variable的协方差矩阵，then, calculate the lambda.
mean(lambda.TFTx) # calculate the mean value of lambda
## [1] 0.7031039
HPDinterval(lambda.TFTx) # Highest Posterior Density Interval
##          lower     upper
## var1 0.3572054 0.9945666
## attr(,"Probability")
## [1] 0.9500525

6. Phylomorphospace construction and principle component analysis (PCA)

cov_model<-readRDS("cov_model_OnSango_sprandom_Final.nosize.20mil.rds")
Eig <- eigen(matrix(summary(cov_model)$Gcovariances,10,10))
## Warning in matrix(summary(cov_model)$Gcovariances, 10, 10): data length differs
## from size of matrix: [400 != 10 x 10]
evectors <- Eig$vectors
rownames(evectors) <- colnames(TPM_information_norm)[2:11]
#Variation explained by individual components
print(round(Eig$values/sum(Eig$values) * 100, digits = 2))
##  [1] 53.60 17.87 13.29  7.25  4.81  1.48  1.18  0.32  0.20  0.00
#Cummulative Variation explained by individual components
print(round(cumsum(Eig$values)/sum(Eig$values) * 100, digits = 2))
##  [1]  53.60  71.47  84.76  92.01  96.82  98.30  99.48  99.80 100.00 100.00
scores <- as.matrix(TPM_information_norm[,2:11]) %*% evectors # calculating scores from eigenanalysis results
rownames(scores)<-TPM_information$species

correlations <- cor(scores, TPM_information_norm[,2:11])
#Fancy PCA
plotData <- TPM_information[,c("PLA2","SVMP","SVSP","TFTx" ,"Family", "species")]
plotData$PCA1 <- scores[,1]
plotData$PCA2 <- scores[,2]
plotData$shortname <- gsub("([A-Z]).*_([a-z]).*", "\\1\\2", plotData$species)
evedata <- evectors
evedata = as.data.frame(evedata)

evedata$components = c("TFTx","BPP","CRISP", "CTL", "GF","KSPI","LAAO","PLA2","SVMP","SVSP")
evedata$colors = c("#fdae61","pink","brown","lightgoldenrod","sienna","lightslategray","navy","#008080","#aa4499","#92c5de")


ggplot(plotData,aes(PCA1, PCA2,label = shortname, xl))+
  geom_scatterpie(aes(x=PCA1, y=PCA2), data=plotData, cols=c("PLA2","SVMP","SVSP","TFTx"))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("#008080","#aa4499","#92c5de","#fdae61"))+
  geom_label_repel(aes(color = Family))+
  geom_segment(aes(0,0, xend = evedata[,1]*2, yend = evedata[,2]*2), color= evedata$colors , data = evedata,arrow = arrow(), linewidth = 1, show.legend = F ,inherit.aes = F)+
  theme_light()

## increasing max.overlaps

7. Convergence analysis

7.1. Introduction

  • Firstly we need to notice the difference between convergence and parallel. Although either represents evidence for convergence at the phenotypic level, they have different genetic and developmental basis.

  • Source of convergence: (1) random walk (Brownian motion), especially if trait space is low dimensional; (2) adaptation to shared environments (the frequency of convergence should be distinguishable), such as ecomorph species.

  • Flaws of present detection methods: The a priori identification of ecomorphs creates the potential for bias in tests for convergence. Reason (1) nonecomorph species may be ignored; (2) an element of circularity if those traits played any role in ecomorph designation.

  • A new method for identifying convergent evolution —— SURFACE (SURFACE Uses Regime Fitting with Akaike Information Criterion (AIC) to model Convergent Evolution): without the a priori designation of ecomorphs or selective regimes.

  • We used the default Ornstein-Uhlenbeck (OU) process, a convenient representation of evolution towards adaptive peaks for modelling convergence in the SURFACE analysis. The SURFACE method uses Hansen’s approach (Hansen model) of modelling evolution towards different adaptive optima by painting multiple adaptive hypothesis onto branches of a phylogenetic tree. SURFACE is unique because, the placements of regime shifts is guided by trait data. However, previous methods that utilize Hansen models, use some a priori hypothesis regarding the location of convergence. The SURFACE method is divided into two phases:

    1. The forward phase adds successive regimes to a basic Hansen model using input from continuous trait measurements(用连续性性状的观测值，不断向Hansen model里添加新的适应性区段), which in our study were normalized measurements of gene expression for the four major toxins. The performance of each successive model was measured using AIC by balancing improvements in log-likelihood against increase in model complexity. Since AIC (Akaike Information Criterion) for the models are calculated after adding log-likelihoods, the AIC for successive models may improve. The regime shift representing the best model is painted onto the tree.
    1. The backwards phase is the second phase in the analysis. During this phase of SURFACE all subsets of regimes are collapsed to yield distinct regimes. The collapse is continued till the AIC of the models does not increase further.

  • The final model has k regime shifts, and k’ distinct regimes, in addition to the extent of convergence which is defined as the difference of these terms (Δk), c is used to represent the the shifts towards different convergent regimes in multiple lineages (Ingram 2013). We used all standard parameters as mentioned in the SURFACE vignette (Ingram 2013) and used the first two principal components as input. To obtain a null distribution we ran 500 iterations of the in-built surfaceSimulate function using a Hansen-fit model, and concatenated the output from each iteration.
